43d\u0456\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u043c \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0438 \u0432\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043e \u043e\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0456 \u043f\u0440\u0456\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0442\u0438 \u0444\u0456\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0441\u0443\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044f \u043d\u0430 2019 \u0440\u0456\u043a}}</ref>\n| ranked             = 29\n| reserve            = 1,000,000 (2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unian.info/society/1541926-ukraines-defense-ministry-elaborates-on-military-reserve.html|title=Ukraine's Defense Ministry elaborates on military reserve|publisher=UNIAN|access-date=2016-10-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160930131639/http://www.unian.info/society/1541926-ukraines-defense-ministry-elaborates-on-military-reserve.html|archive-date=2016-09-30|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| deployed           = 60,000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unian.net/war/1094445-poroshenko-v-zone-ato-nahodyatsya-60-tyisyach-ukrainskih-voennoslujaschih.html|title=\u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e: \u0412 \u0437\u043e\u043d\u0435 \u0410\u0422\u041e \u043d\u0430\u0445\u043e\u0434\u044f\u0442\u0441\u044f 60 \u0442\u044b\u0441\u044f\u0447 \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0430\u0449\u0438\u0445|publisher=UNIAN|access-date=2015-06-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150627191154/http://www.unian.net/war/1094445-poroshenko-v-zone-ato-nahodyatsya-60-tyisyach-ukrainskih-voennoslujaschih.html|archive-date=2015-06-27|url-status=live}}</ref>\n<!-- Financial -->\n| amount             = [[hryvnia|UAH]] 136 billion ($5.4 billion)(2020)<ref name=\"pravda.com.ua\">https://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2019/10/8/7228477/</ref>\n\n| percent_GDP        = 3% (2020)<ref name=\"pravda.com.ua\" />\n<!-- Industrial -->\n| domestic_suppliers = [[Ukroboronprom]] (Ukrainian Defence Industry)\n| foreign_suppliers  = {{USA}}<ref name=fsUa3816>[U.S. supplies maximum arms to Ukraine: Media], {{AUS}} (3 August 2016)</ref><br />{{UK}}<ref name=fsUa3816 /><br />{{FRA}}<br />{{EU}}<ref name=fsUa3816 /><br />{{AUS}}<ref name=fsUa3816 /><br />{{CAN}}<ref name=fsUa3816 /><br />{{ISR}}<br />{{POL}}<br />{{CZE}}<br />{{TUR}}<br />{{CHN}}<br />{{JPN}}<br />{{GEO}}<br>'''Former''':<br />{{flag|Russia}}<br />{{BLR}}<br />{{Flagcountry|CSR}}<br />{{flagcountry|PPR}}<br />{{flagcountry|PRB}}\n\n| imports            =\n| exports            =\n<!-- Related aricles -->\n| history            =  [[Ukrainian\u2013Soviet War]]<br />[[Polish\u2013Ukrainian War]]<br />[[Autonomous Republic of Crimea|1992\u201394 Crimean crisis]]<br />[[Kosovo Force]]<br />[[UNAMSIL]]<br />[[Tuzla Island#2003 conflict|Tuzla Island conflict]]<br />[[ISAF]]<br />[[Iraq War]]<br />[[United Nations Operation in C\u00f4te d'Ivoire|ONUCI]]<br />[[Operation Ocean Shield]]<br />[[MONUSCO]]<br />[[Operation Atalanta]]<br />[[2014 pro-Russian unrest in Ukraine|Pro-Russian unrest in Ukraine]]<br />[[Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation|Annexation of Crimea]]<br />[[War in Donbass]]\n| ranks              = [[Military ranks of Ukraine]]\n}}\n\n{{Armies of Ukraine}}\n{{Politics of Ukraine}}\n\nThe '''Armed Forces of Ukraine''' ({{lang-uk|\u0417\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0439\u043d\u0456 \u0441\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438}} (\u0417\u0421\u0423) {{lang|uk-Latn|Zbroyni Syly Ukrayiny}}, ('''ZSU''') is the [[military]] of [[Ukraine]]. They are the principal deterrent force against any aggression that could be shown against the sovereign state of Ukraine. All military and security forces, including the Armed Forces, are under the command of the [[President of Ukraine]], and subject to oversight by a permanent [[Verkhovna Rada]] parliamentary commission.\n\nThe Armed Forces of Ukraine are composed of the [[Ukrainian Ground Forces]], the [[Ukrainian Navy]], the [[Ukrainian Air Force]], and the [[Ukrainian Airmobile Forces]]. Ukraine's naval forces maintain their own small [[Ukrainian Naval Infantry]] force as well as their own [[Ukrainian Naval Aviation]] force. The [[Ukrainian Sea Guard]] is the coast guard service of Ukraine, however, it is part of the [[State Border Guard Service of Ukraine]] and is not subordinate to the Navy. As a result of the [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine]] from 2014, the president commissioned governors of [[oblasts of Ukraine]] to create volunteer [[Territorial Defense Battalion of Ukraine|units]] under the government program \"Territorial Defense\". Initially these units received minimal funding coming from regional budgets and mostly relied on donations. In November 2014 most of the territorial battalions were integrated into Ukraine's Ground forces.\n\nThe [[National Guard of Ukraine]] serves as the main reserve component of Armed Forces of Ukraine.\n\nDue to the ongoing hostilities with Russia, Ukraine has greatly increased the size of its military forces to 204,000 soldiers (+46,000 civil servants) in 2014, not counting paramilitary forces such as the border guards (53,000), the newly formed National Guard of Ukraine (60,000) or the security service.<ref>{{Cite news |url= http://www.dw.com/en/ukraine-plans-to-double-military-budget-against-fighting-in-east/a-18125986 |title = Ukraine plans to double military budget against fighting in east |date=12 December 2014|work = [[Deutsche Welle]]|access-date = 9 February 2016|via = |archive-date = 9 February 2016|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160209210320/http://www.dw.com/en/ukraine-plans-to-double-military-budget-against-fighting-in-east/a-18125986}}</ref> The size Ukraine's armed forces came close to France, which maintained a 229,000 man force, as the largest in Europe when excluding Russia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalfirepower.com/country-military-strength-detail.asp?country_id=france|publisher=Global Fire Power|title=France|access-date=2014-12-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229115238/http://www.globalfirepower.com/country-military-strength-detail.asp?country_id=france|archive-date=2014-12-29|url-status=live}}</ref> It was reported that Ukraine's military swelled to 280,000 personnel. This was largely achieved by the repeated waves of mobilization bringing in new recruits while older soldiers had not yet been processed out, the state budget for 2015 ultimately called for a force of 230,000. [[Hryhoriy Pedchenko]] reported that 51% of Ukraine's enlisted personnel were contracted soldiers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hromadskeradio.org/2015/09/13/za-ostanniy-rik-ukrayinska-armiya-zrosla-vid-146-do-280-tysyach-poltorak|title=During the last year, the Ukrainian army grew from 146 up to 280 thousand, - Poltorak|access-date=2015-09-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208062910/http://hromadskeradio.org/2015/09/13/za-ostanniy-rik-ukrayinska-armiya-zrosla-vid-146-do-280-tysyach-poltorak|archive-date=2015-12-08|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/ukraine/personnel.htm|title=Ukrainian Military Personnel|access-date=2014-12-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141222230712/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/ukraine/personnel.htm|archive-date=2014-12-22|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMilitary units of other states participate in multinational military exercises with Ukrainian forces in Ukraine regularly.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.kyivpost.com/article/content/ukraine-politics/parliament-approves-admission-of-military-units-of-67094.html|title = Parliament approves admission of military units of foreign states to Ukraine for exercises|last = |first = |date = 18 May 2010|work = [[Kyiv Post]]|access-date = 9 February 2016|via = |archive-date = 9 February 2016|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160209205601/http://www.kyivpost.com/article/content/ukraine-politics/parliament-approves-admission-of-military-units-of-67094.html}}</ref> Many of these exercises are held under the NATO co-operation program [[Partnership for Peace]].\n\nSince 3 June 2016, women have been allowed to serve in combat units of the Armed Forces.<ref name=waiUm3616>[http://www.unian.info/society/1451743-war-has-a-female-face.html War has a female face] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160804185149/http://www.unian.info/society/1451743-war-has-a-female-face.html |date=2016-08-04 }}, [[UNIAN]] (4 August 2016)</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Origins of the post-1992 Ukrainian Armed Forces ===\n{{As of | 1992}}, the Ukrainian Armed Forces were completely inherited from the [[Soviet Union]], in which Ukraine [[Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic|had been a member state]] (a [[union republic]]). Like other Soviet republics, it did not possess its own separate military command, as all military formations were uniformly subordinated to the central command of the [[Armed Forces of the USSR]]. Administratively, the [[Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic|Ukrainian SSR]] was divided into three Soviet military districts (the [[Carpathian Military District]], [[Kiev]] [[Kiev Military District|Military District]], and [[Odesa]] [[Odessa Military District|Military District]]). Three Soviet air commands and most of the [[Black Sea Fleet]] naval bases were located on the coast of Ukraine.\n\nWhen the [[collapse of the Soviet Union]] took place in 1991 (see [[Novo-Ogaryovo]] process), the newly-independent state of Ukraine inherited one of the most powerful force groupings in Europe. According to an associate of the [[Conflict Studies Research Centre]], James Sherr: \"This grouping, its inventory of equipment and its officer corps was designed for one purpose: to wage combined arms, coalition, offensive (and nuclear) warfare against NATO on an external front\".<ref>James Sherr, 'Ukraine's Defense Reform: An Update', [[Conflict Studies Research Centre]], 2002</ref> At that time, the former Soviet armed forces in the [[Ukrainian SSR]] included a rocket army ([[43rd Rocket Army]]), four air-force armies, an air-defense army ([[8th Air Defence Army]]), three regular armies, two tank armies, the [[32nd Army Corps (Soviet Union)|32nd Army Corps]], and the [[Black Sea Fleet]].<ref>[http://vijsko.milua.org/i4.htm \u0421\u0442\u0430\u043d \u0417\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0439\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u0421\u0438\u043b \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u043c\u043e\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442 \u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044f (Status of the Armed Forces of Ukraine at the time of creation)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120531092727/http://vijsko.milua.org/i4.htm |date=2012-05-31 }}. Ukrainian Military in 20-21st centuries.</ref> Altogether the Armed Forces of Ukraine included about 780,000 personnel, 6,500 tanks, about 7,000 combat armored vehicles, 1,500 combat [[aircraft]], and more than 350 ships.  Along with their equipment and personnel, Ukraine's armed forces inherited the battle honors and lineage of the Soviet forces stationed in Ukraine. However, due to the deterioration of Russian-Ukrainian relations and to the continued stigma of being associated with the Soviet Union, in 2015 the [[President of Ukraine]] ordered the removal of most of the citations awarded to the Ukrainian units during the Soviet era.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.president.gov.ua/documents/6462015-19568|script-title=uk:\u0423\u041a\u0410\u0417 \u041f\u0420\u0415\u0417\u0418\u0414\u0415\u041d\u0422\u0410 \u0423\u041a\u0420\u0410\u0407\u041d\u0418 \u2116646/2015|publisher= Official website of the President of Ukraine|access-date= 2017-06-15|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160831090416/http://www.president.gov.ua/documents/6462015-19568|archive-date= 2016-08-31|url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 February 1991, a parliamentary Standing Commission for Questions of Security and Defense was established. On August 24, 1991, the Ukrainian parliament (the [[Verkhovna Rada]]), in adopting the [[Declaration of Independence of Ukraine]], also enacted a short resolution \"About military formations in Ukraine\".<ref>Law of Ukraine N 1431-XII. \"[http://zakon4.rada.gov.ua/laws/show/1431-12 About military formations of Ukraine] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140302202649/http://zakon4.rada.gov.ua/laws/show/1431-12 |date=2014-03-02 }}\". [[Verkhovna Rada]]. August 24, 1991.</ref> This took jurisdiction over all formations of the armed forces of the Soviet Union stationed on Ukrainian soil and established one of the key agencies, the [[Ministry of Defense (Ukraine)|Ukrainian Ministry of Defense]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.mil.gov.ua/index.php?lang=en&part=history&sub=history|title= \u041c\u0456\u043d\u0456\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e|access-date= 2008-05-07|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20071015192107/http://www.mil.gov.ua/index.php?lang=en&part=history&sub=history|archive-date= 2007-10-15|url-status= live}}</ref> On 3 September 1991, the Ministry of Defence commenced its duties. On 22 October 1991 units and formations of the Soviet Armed Forces on Ukrainian soil were nationalized.<ref>James Sherr, DEFENCE & SECURITY REFORM IN UKRAINE: A FRESH START? (''Survival'', Spring 2001)</ref> Subsequently, the Supreme Council of Ukraine adopted two Laws of Ukraine on December 6, 1991,<ref>[http://zakon4.rada.gov.ua/laws/show/1932-12 Official document] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130215191800/http://zakon4.rada.gov.ua/laws/show/1932-12 |date=2013-02-15 }}. Law of Ukraine \"About Defense of Ukraine\". December 6, 1991</ref><ref>[http://zakon4.rada.gov.ua/laws/show/1934-12 Official document] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130309010758/http://zakon4.rada.gov.ua/laws/show/1934-12 |date=2013-03-09 }}. Law of Ukraine \"About Armed Forces of Ukraine. December 6, 1991</ref> and Presidential Ukase #4 \"About Armed Forces of Ukraine\" on December 12, 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://zakon4.rada.gov.ua/laws/show/4/91|title= \u041f\u0440\u043e \u0417\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0439\u043d\u0456 \u0421\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 - \u0432\u0456\u0434 12 December 1991 \u2116 4|website= zakon4.rada.gov.ua|access-date= 28 January 2013|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140302202536/http://zakon4.rada.gov.ua/laws/show/4/91|archive-date= 2 March 2014|url-status= live|df= dmy-all}}</ref> The government of Ukraine surrendered any rights of succession to the Soviet Strategic Deterrence Forces<ref>[http://encyclopedia.mil.ru/encyclopedia/dictionary/details_rvsn.htm?id=14378@morfDictionary Strategic Deterrence Forces] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160204213433/http://encyclopedia.mil.ru/encyclopedia/dictionary/details_rvsn.htm?id=14378@morfDictionary |date=2016-02-04 }} at encyclopedia.mil.ru</ref> (see [[Strategic Missile Troops]]) that were staged on the territory of Ukraine. Recognizing the complications of a smooth transition and seeking a consensus with other former members of the Soviet Union in dividing up their Soviet military inheritance, Ukraine joined ongoing talks that started in December 1991<ref>{{cite web|url= http://pravo.levonevsky.org/bazaby/mdogov/megd4608.htm|title= \u0421\u043e\u0433\u043b\u0430\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043e \u0421\u0438\u043b\u0430\u0445 \u043e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0433\u043e \u043d\u0430\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043d\u0430 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0445\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043e\u0434 - \u041c\u0435\u0436\u0434\u0443\u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0434\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0440\u044b|website= pravo.levonevsky.org|access-date= 2013-01-28|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130512044748/http://pravo.levonevsky.org/bazaby/mdogov/megd4608.htm|archive-date= 2013-05-12|url-status= live}}</ref> regarding a [[:ru:\u041e\u0431\u044a\u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0451\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0412\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0451\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0421\u0438\u043b\u044b \u0421\u041d\u0413|joint military command]] of the [[Commonwealth of Independent States]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.lawrussia.ru/texts/legal_383/doc383a830x976.htm|title= \u0421\u041e\u0413\u041b\u0410\u0428\u0415\u041d\u0418\u0415 \u041e\u0411 \u041e\u0411\u042a\u0415\u0414\u0418\u041d\u0415\u041d\u041d\u042b\u0425 \u0412\u041e\u041e\u0420\u0423\u0416\u0415\u041d\u041d\u042b\u0425 \u0421\u0418\u041b\u0410\u0425 \u041d\u0410 \u041f\u0415\u0420\u0415\u0425\u041e\u0414\u041d\u042b\u0419 \u041f\u0415\u0420\u0418\u041e\u0414 (\u041a\u0418\u0415\u0412, 20.03.92)|website= lawrussia.ru|access-date= 2013-01-28|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130730163948/http://www.lawrussia.ru/texts/legal_383/doc383a830x976.htm|archive-date= 2013-07-30|url-status= dead}}</ref>\n\nInherent in the process of creating a domestic military were political decisions by the Ukrainian leadership regarding the country's non-nuclear and international status. Among these were the definition, agreement, and ratification of the 1990 [[Treaty on Conventional Armed Forces in Europe]] (CFE) which not only established the maximum level of armament for each republic of the former USSR, but also a special ceiling for the so-called CFE \"Flank Region\". Included in this region were Ukraine's [[Mykolaiv Oblast|Mykolaiv]], [[Kherson Oblast|Kherson]] and [[Zaporizhia Oblast]]s, and the [[Autonomous Republic of Crimea]]. Another key event in the development of the Ukrainian military was the [[Collective Security Treaty Organization|1992 Tashkent Treaty]], which laid out aspirations for a [[Commonwealth of Independent States]] military. This collective military proved impossible to develop because the former republics of the USSR all wished to go their own way, ripping the intricate Soviet military machine into pieces.\n\nUkraine had observer status with the [[Non-Aligned Movement]] of nation-states from 1996.<ref>{{Cite web |title = NAM Background Information |url = http://www.nam.gov.za/background/background.htm#4.2 |website = www.nam.gov.za |access-date = 2016-02-09 |archive-date = 9 February 2016 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160209210107/http://www.nam.gov.za/background/background.htm}}</ref> However, due to the [[2014 Russian aggression against Ukraine]], the [[Verkhovna Rada]] repealed this status on 23 December 2014.<ref>\n{{Cite news\n | url = http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/241359.html\n | title = Ukraine abolishes its non-aligned status \u2013 law\n | last = | first = | date = 23 December 2014\n | work = [[Interfax Ukraine]]\n | access-date = 9 February 2016 |via =\n | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141224003612/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/241359.html\n | archive-date = 24 December 2014\n}}\n</ref>\n\n=== Arms Control and Disarmament ===\n[[File:TU-22 scrapyard.jpg|thumb|left|A [[Tu-22M]] being dismantled through assistance provided by the Cooperative Threat Reduction Program implemented by the [[Defense Threat Reduction Agency|DTRA]], 2002]]\n\n{{See also|Nuclear weapons and Ukraine}}\n\nFollowing the breakup of the Soviet Union, Ukraine inherited two divisions of the [[Strategic Rocket Forces]]' [[43rd Rocket Army]] (HQ [[Vinnytsia]]): the 19th Rocket Division ([[Khmelnytskyi, Ukraine|Khmelnytskyi]]) (90 [[UR-100N]]/SS-19/RS-18) and the [[46th Rocket Division]] at [[Pervomaisk, Mykolaiv Oblast]], equipped with 40 SS-19 and 46 silo-mounted [[RT-23 Molodets]]/SS-24s.<ref>Source old early 1990s notes, but corroboration available for example at [http://www.traveltoukraine.org/Ukraine_secret_sites.htm traveltoukraine.org and Feskov et al. 2004] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080412083546/http://www.traveltoukraine.org/Ukraine_secret_sites.htm |date=2008-04-12 }}</ref> While Ukraine had physical control of these systems, it did not have operational control. The use of the weapons was dependent on Russian-controlled electronic [[Permissive Action Link]]s and the Russian command and control system.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MNanc3lYUsQC |chapter=Why Ukraine gave up nuclear weapons : nonproliferation incentives and disincentives |author=William C. Martel |pages=88\u2013104 |title=Pulling Back from the Nuclear Brink: Reducing and Countering Nuclear Threats |editor=Barry R. Schneider, William L. Dowdy |publisher=Psychology Press |year=1998 |isbn=978-0-7146-4856-9 |accessdate=6 August 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160204213432/https://books.google.com/books?id=MNanc3lYUsQC |archive-date=4 February 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"pikayev-1994\">{{cite journal |url=http://cns.miis.edu/npr/pdfs/pikaye13.pdf |title=Post-Soviet Russia and Ukraine: Who can push the Button? |author=Alexander A. Pikayev |journal=The Nonproliferation Review |volume=1 |issue=3 |pages=31\u201346 |date=Spring\u2013Summer 1994 |doi=10.1080/10736709408436550 |accessdate=6 August 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521083227/http://cns.miis.edu/npr/pdfs/pikaye13.pdf |archive-date=21 May 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[File:SS20 irbm.jpg|thumb|left|A [[SS-20]] on display at the [[National Museum of the History of Ukraine in the Second World War|World War II Museum in Kiev]]]]\n\nUkraine voluntarily gave up these and all other nuclear weapons during the early 1990s. This was the first time in history that a country voluntarily gave up the use of strategic nuclear weapons, although the [[Republic of South Africa]] was dismantling its small tactical nuclear weapons program at about the same time.\n\nUkraine has plentiful amounts of highly [[enriched uranium]], which the United States wanted to buy from the [[Kharkiv Institute of Physics and Technology]]. Ukraine also has two [[uranium]] mining and processing factories, a [[heavy water]] plant and technology for determining the [[isotope|isotopic]] composition of [[Nuclear fission|fissionable]] materials. Ukraine has deposits of uranium that are among the world's richest. In May 1992, Ukraine signed the [[START I|Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty]] ([[START I]]) in which the country agreed to give up all [[nuclear weapon]]s and to join the [[Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty]] as a non-nuclear weapon state. Ukraine ratified the treaty in 1994, and as of January 1, 1996, no military nuclear equipment or materials remain on Ukrainian territory.\n\nOn 13 May 1994, the [[United States]] and [[Ukraine]] signed a Memorandum of Understanding on the Transfer of Missile Equipment and Technology. This agreement committed Ukraine to the Missile Technology Control Regime ([[MTCR]]) by controlling [[exports]] of [[missile]]-related equipment and technology according to the MTCR Guidelines.\n\nOther disarmament \u2013 strategic planes & other missiles\n\nUkraine and [[NATO]] estimate that 2.5 million tons of conventional ammunition were left in Ukraine as the Soviet military withdrew, as well as more than 7 million rifles, pistols, mortars, and machine guns. The surplus weapons and ammunition were stored in over 180 military bases, including in bunkers, salt mines and in the open.<ref name=\"nyt-20050716\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/07/16/international/europe/16ammo.html |title=Ill-Secured Soviet Arms Depots Tempting Rebels and Terrorists |author=C. J. Chivers |newspaper=New York Times |date=16 July 2005 |accessdate=15 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141214124434/http://www.nytimes.com/2005/07/16/international/europe/16ammo.html |archive-date=14 December 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> As of 2014, much of this surplus had not been scrapped.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.sky.com/story/1252613/ukraine-militia-controls-a-million-weapons |title=Ukraine: Militia Controls A Million Weapons |author=Stuart Ramsay |newspaper=Sky News |date=1 May 2014 |accessdate=15 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503034729/http://news.sky.com/story/1252613/ukraine-militia-controls-a-million-weapons |archive-date=3 May 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://defensetech.org/2012/06/05/tanks-as-far-as-the-eye-can-see/ |title=Soviet Tanks As Far As The Eye Can See |author=John Reed |newspaper=Defense Tech |date=5 June 2012 |accessdate=15 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140901171341/http://defensetech.org/2012/06/05/tanks-as-far-as-the-eye-can-see/ |archive-date=1 September 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Attempt at Reforms and Constant Fund Shortages ===\n\nUkraine's first military reforms began on December 26, 1996, with the adoption of a new \"State Program for the Building and Development of the Armed Forces of Ukraine\". One of the aspects was to shrink the standard combat unit from division size to brigade size which would then fall under the command of one of the three newly created military district; the [[Operation Command West|Western Operational Command]], the [[Southern Operational Command]], and the largest \u2013 the [[Operation Command North|Northern Operational/Territorial Command]].<ref>Wolchik, p.75, 91, original newspaper sources include Kyivska Pravda, 10 November 1992, in FBIS-SOV, 2 December 1992, 18, and [http://na.mil.gov.ua/ ''Narodna Armiia''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023050800/http://na.mil.gov.ua/ |date=2012-10-23 }}, 18 January 1997.</ref> Only Ukraine's [[1st Airmobile Division (Ukraine)|1st Airmobile Division]] was not downsized. This downsizing occurred purely for financial reasons with Ukrainian economy in recession this was a way to shrink the government (defense) expenditure and at the same time release hundreds of thousands of young people into the private sector to stimulate growth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NY.GDP.MKTP.KD.ZG?page=3|title=GDP growth (annual %)|work=The World Bank|accessdate=13 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304205024/http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NY.GDP.MKTP.KD.ZG?page=3|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> During this time Ukraine's [[military-industrial complex]] also began to develop new indigenous weapons for the armed forces like the [[T-84]] tank, the [[BMP-1]]U, the [[BTR-3]], [[KrAZ-6322]], and the [[Antonov An-70]]. All these reforms were championed by [[Leonid Kuchma]], the 2nd President of Ukraine, who wanted to retain a capable military and a functioning military-industrial complex because he didn't trust Russia who he believed might one day become Ukraine's enemy, stating once \"The threat of Russofication is a real concern for us\".<ref>Kuzio Taras, p.457, Praeger Security International , [https://books.google.com/books?id=CqXACQAAQBAJ&pg=PA464&lpg=PA464&dq=ukraine+armed+forces+in+1990s&source=bl&ots=p9l3YPqJMg&sig=UvMIaCONN3TL6hklRt0R_jyBS_E&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjHsfruhPTKAhVGw2MKHWZqDrkQ6AEIajAM#v=onepage&q=ukraine%20armed%20forces%20in%201990s&f=false ''Ukraine: Democratization, Corruption, and the New Russian Imperialism''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170321045855/https://books.google.com/books?id=CqXACQAAQBAJ&pg=PA464&lpg=PA464&dq=ukraine+armed+forces+in+1990s&source=bl&ots=p9l3YPqJMg&sig=UvMIaCONN3TL6hklRt0R_jyBS_E&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjHsfruhPTKAhVGw2MKHWZqDrkQ6AEIajAM#v=onepage&q=ukraine%20armed%20forces%20in%201990s&f=false |date=2017-03-21 }}, 2015.</ref>\n\nKuchma was also eager to modernize the equipment of the Ukrainian Armed Forces, however, after learning of the price tag of such a move, he backtracked, preferring to rely on the sizable Soviet supply of weapons which he made sure were well maintained.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}} But the cancellation of the modernization program left a question of how to provide jobs in the military industrial complex which then comprised a double-digit percentage of the GDP. Export of new and modernized weapons on the world's arms markets was settled on as the best option, where Ukraine both tried to undercut the contracts of the Russian arms industry \u2013 offering the same service for a cheaper price, and was willing to sell equipment to whoever was willing to pay (more than once to politically unstable or even aggressive regimes), causing negative reactions from both [[Western Europe]] and the [[United States federal government]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://iipdigital.usembassy.gov/st/english/article/2002/09/20020925141643jthomas@pd.state.gov7.893008e-02.html#axzz43xckFL5r| title=TU.S. Suspends Some Aid to Ukraine Over Kolchuga Sale to Iraq| work=IIP Digital| date=24 September 2002| accessdate=25 March 2016| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160406130605/http://iipdigital.usembassy.gov/st/english/article/2002/09/20020925141643jthomas@pd.state.gov7.893008e-02.html#axzz43xckFL5r| archive-date=6 April 2016| url-status=live| df=dmy-all}}</ref> During this time 320 [[T-80]] tanks would be sold to [[Pakistan]] and an unfinished Soviet aircraft carrier the Varyag which today is known as the [[Chinese aircraft carrier Liaoning]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/1681755/how-xu-zengping-became-middleman-chinas-deal-buy-liaoning| title=The inside story of the Liaoning: how Xu Zengping sealed deal for China's first aircraft carrier| author=Minnie Chan| work=[[South China Morning Post]]| date=19 January 2015| accessdate=25 March 2016| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322174406/http://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/1681755/how-xu-zengping-became-middleman-chinas-deal-buy-liaoning| archive-date=22 March 2016| url-status=live| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThough the military was well equipped it still experienced lack of funds particularly for training and exercises, which led to a number of incidents with one notable one being the [[Siberia Airlines Flight 1812]] of 2001 the other [[Sknyliv airshow disaster]] of 2002. Still, the military's effectiveness was demonstrated during the [[Tuzla Island]] Conflict \u2013 when (brief description). In 2003 Ukraine completed its first set of reforms which were judged largely successful, with the personnel numbers stabilizing at 295,000 of which 90,000 were civilian contractors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/ukraine/personnel|title=Ukrainian Military Personnel |work=GlobalSecurity.org |accessdate=13 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n*Second phase 2004\u20132010\n** downsizing further\n**training\n**maintenance and new equipment\n**NATO and Russia\n**2008 financial crisis\n*The Yanukovich Catastrophe (2011\u20132014)<ref>{{Cite web |title = Ukraine Defense Doctrine |url = http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/ukraine/doctrine.htm |website = www.globalsecurity.org |access-date = 2016-02-14 |first = John |last = Pike |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160216145935/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/ukraine/doctrine.htm |archive-date = 2016-02-16 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n# appointment of Russian citizens to the ministry of defense and intelligence\n# downsizing\n# lack of funds for exercise, vehicle maintenance, and even monthly paychecks\n# scrapping and sale of equipment\n# incompetence in, and destruction of the military industrial complex\n\nUkrainian military tactics and organization are heavily dependent on [[Cold War]] tactics and former [[Soviet Armed Forces]] organization. Under former President Yushchenko, Ukraine pursued a policy of independence from Russian dominance, and thus tried to fully integrate with the West, specifically NATO.\n\nUntil the Euromaidan crisis of 2014, Ukraine retained tight military relations with [[Russia]], inherited from their common Soviet history. Common uses for naval bases in the [[Autonomous Republic of Crimea|Crimea]] and joint [[air defense]] efforts were the most intense cooperative efforts. This cooperation was a permanent irritant in bilateral relations, but Ukraine appeared economically dependent on Moscow, and thus unable to break such ties quickly. After the election of President Victor Yanukovych, ties between Moscow and Kiev warmed, and those between Kiev and NATO cooled, relative to the Yushchenko years.\n\n=== Conflict in Southeastern Ukraine (2014 \u2013 present) ===\n[[File:Anti-terrorist operation in eastern Ukraine (28137543322).jpg|thumb|T-64BMs in Eastern Ukraine]]\n{{Main|2014 Crimean crisis|Donbass War|War crimes during the war in Donbass}}\n\nIn March 2014, after the Crimean crisis began, it was announced by the reformist government that a new military service, the [[National Guard of Ukraine]] would be created. Previously a National Guard had existed up until 2000, thus the 2014 NG is a reformation of the one raised in 1991, but this time formed part of personnel from the [[Internal Troops of Ukraine]].\n\nIn May 2014 with war happening in eastern regions, a helicopter with 14 soldiers on board including General Serhiy Kulchytskiy, who headed combat and special training for the country's National Guard, was brought down by militants near [[Sloviansk]] in East Ukraine. Outgoing President Olexander Turchynov described the downing as a \"terrorist attack,\" and blamed pro-Russian militants.<ref name=\"HelicopterDowning\">{{cite news|title=General, 13 soldiers killed as militants down military helicopter|url=http://www.russiaherald.com/index.php/sid/222436237/scat/723971d98160d438/ht/General-13-soldiers-killed-as-militants-down-military-helicopter|accessdate=29 May 2014|publisher=Russia Herald|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140531092102/http://www.russiaherald.com/index.php/sid/222436237/scat/723971d98160d438/ht/General-13-soldiers-killed-as-militants-down-military-helicopter|archive-date=31 May 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn the early months of the [[War in Donbass]], the Armed Forces were widely criticised for their poor equipment and inept leadership, forcing Internal Affairs Ministry forces like the [[National Guard of Ukraine|National Guard]] and the [[Territorial defence battalion (Ukraine)|territorial defence battalions]] to take on the brunt of the fighting in the first months of the war.<ref name=\"KP23215b\">{{cite news |url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/abandoned-donbas-battalion-fights-on-361886.html |title=Abandoned Donbas Battalion fights on |work=Kyiv Post |date=24 August 2014 |accessdate=27 August 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140825135333/http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/abandoned-donbas-battalion-fights-on-361886.html |archive-date=25 August 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"NR9MAYb\">{{cite news |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/117710/ukraines-army-small-sovietized-underfunded-and-poorly-trained |title=Why is Ukraine's Army So Appallingly Bad? |work=The New Republic |date=9 May 2014 |accessdate=20 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140704053656/http://www.newrepublic.com/article/117710/ukraines-army-small-sovietized-underfunded-and-poorly-trained |archive-date=4 July 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn late July 2015, the Ukrainian Defense Ministry revealed new Ukrainian Armed Forces uniform designs, later a revised rank insignia system was created.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.unian.info/war/1105338-ukraines-defense-ministry-presents-new-military-uniform.html|title=Ukraine's Defense Ministry presents new military uniform|last=|first=|date=27 July 2015|work=[[UNIAN]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160302214406/http://www.unian.info/war/1105338-ukraines-defense-ministry-presents-new-military-uniform.html|archive-date=2 March 2016|access-date=27 July 2015|via=}}</ref> These made their national debut on August 24, 2016, at the National Independence Day Silver Jubilee parade in Independence Square, [[Kiev]].\n\nBy February 2018 the Ukrainian armed forces were larger and better equipped than ever before, numbering 200,000 active-service military personnel and most of the volunteer soldiers of the territorial defence battalions have been integrated into the official Ukrainian army.<ref>[https://carnegieendowment.org/2018/02/22/ukraine-s-toughest-fight-challenge-of-military-reform-pub-75609 Ukraine\u2019s Toughest Fight: The Challenge of Military Reform] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181003014204/https://carnegieendowment.org/2018/02/22/ukraine-s-toughest-fight-challenge-of-military-reform-pub-75609 |date=2018-10-03 }}, [[Carnegie Endowment for International Peace]] (FEBRUARY 22, 2018)</ref>\n\nA late 2017-early 2018 [[United Nations]] Human Rights Monitoring Mission in Ukraine reported that human rights abuses allegedly committed by Ukrainian security forces and armed groups remain an ongoing issue of the [[War in Donbass]] that erupted in 2014. The nature of the alleged crimes ranges from unlawful or arbitrary detention to torture, ill-treatment and/or sexual violence. Within the reporting period of 16 November 2017 to 15 February 2018 the [[OHCHR]] monitoring mission documented 115 cases of credible allegations of human rights violations committed by both sides of the conflict since 2014.<ref>[https://www.ohchr.org/Documents/Countries/UA/ReportUkraineNov2017-Feb2018_EN.pdf Report on the human rights situation in Ukraine 16 November 2017 to 15 February 2018] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180503041356/http://www.ohchr.org/Documents/Countries/UA/ReportUkraineNov2017-Feb2018_EN.pdf |date=3 May 2018 }}, [[OHCHR]] (page 6)</ref>\n\n=== Ukraine & NATO Membership ===\n[[File:Armyinform006.jpg|thumb|right|250px|SSO operators during exercises]]\n{{Main|Ukraine\u2013NATO relations}}\nUkraine's stated national policy is [[Atlanticism|Euro-Atlantic]] integration, with the [[European Union]]. Ukraine has a \"Distinctive Partnership\" with NATO (see [[Enlargement of NATO]]) and has been an active participant in [[Partnership for Peace]] exercises and in peacekeeping in the [[Balkan]]s. This close relationship with [[NATO]] has been most apparent in Ukrainian cooperation and combined peacekeeping operations with its neighbor Poland in Kosovo. Ukrainian servicemen also serve under NATO command in Iraq, Afghanistan and in [[Operation Active Endeavour]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mil.gov.ua/index.php?lang=ua&part=news&sub=read&id=11248|title=\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0438 \u0423\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0456\u043d\u043d\u044f \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0441-\u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0438 \u041c\u041e<!-- Bot generated title -->|access-date=2008-02-15|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120805053605/www.mil.gov.ua/index.php?lang=ua&part=news&sub=read&id=11248|archive-date=2012-08-05|url-status=dead}}</ref> Former [[Ukrainian President]] [[Viktor Yanukovych]] considered the level of co-operation between [[Ukraine\u2013NATO relations|Ukraine and NATO]] sufficient.<ref name=NATOTAK>[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/63797/ NATO confirms readiness for Ukraine's joining organization] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100419050336/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/63797/ |date=2010-04-19 }}, ''[[Kyiv Post]]'' (April 13, 2010)</ref> His predecessor [[Viktor Yushchenko]] had asked for Ukrainian membership by early 2008.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/7322830.stm Bush to back Ukraine's Nato hopes] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305232437/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/7322830.stm |date=2014-03-05 }}, [[BBC News]] (April 1, 2008)</ref><ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/learningenglish/newsenglish/witn/2008/04/080404_ukraine_nato.shtml NATO membership for Georgia and Ukraine held off] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110202090443/http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/learningenglish/newsenglish/witn/2008/04/080404_ukraine_nato.shtml |date=2011-02-02 }}, [[BBC]] (April 4, 2008)</ref> During the [[2008 Bucharest summit]] NATO declared that Ukraine will become a member of NATO whenever it wants and when it meets the criteria for accession.<ref name=NATOTAK /> Former [[President of Ukraine|Ukrainian President]] [[Viktor Yanukovych|Yanukovych]] opted to keep Ukraine a non-aligned state. This materialized on June 3, 2010 when the [[Verkhovna Rada|Ukrainian parliament]] excluded, with 226 votes, the goal of \"integration into Euro-Atlantic security and NATO membership\" from the country's national security strategy.<ref>[http://euobserver.com/24/30212 Ukraine drops NATO membership bid], [[EUobserver]] (June 6, 2010)</ref> Amid the [[Euromaidan]] unrest, Yanukovych fled Ukraine in February 2014.<ref name=\"result of Russia UNR\" />\n\nThe interim [[First Yatsenyuk Government|Yatsenyuk Government]] which came to power, initially said, with reference to the country's non-aligned status, that it had no plans to join NATO.<ref name=NNUIU29314>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/198372.html Deschytsia states new government of Ukraine has no intention to join NATO] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160215161826/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/198372.html |date=2016-02-15 }}, [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (29 March 2014)</ref> However, following the [[2014 Russian military intervention in Ukraine|Russian military intervention in Ukraine]] and [[2014 Ukrainian parliamentary election|parliamentary elections]] in October 2014, the new government made joining NATO a priority.<ref name=\"rferl.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rferl.org/content/ukraine-parliament-coalition-agreement/26703123.html|title=New Ukraine Coalition Agreed, Sets NATO As Priority|date=2014-11-22|accessdate=2014-11-22|publisher=[[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141121231923/http://www.rferl.org/content/ukraine-parliament-coalition-agreement/26703123.html|archive-date=2014-11-21|url-status=live}}</ref> On 23 December 2014, the Ukrainian parliament renounced Ukraine's [[Country neutrality (international relations)|non-aligned status]]<ref name=\"result of Russia UNR\">[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/241388.html Ukraine has no alternative to Euro-Atlantic integration \u2013 Ukraine has no alternative to Euro-Atlantic integration \u2013 Poroshenko] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304060210/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/241388.html |date=2016-03-04 }}, [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (23 December 2014)</ref><ref name=wsjends>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-ends-nonaligned-status-earning-quick-rebuke-from-russia-1419339226 Ukraine Ends \u2018Nonaligned\u2019 Status, Earning Quick Rebuke From Russia] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304222433/http://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-ends-nonaligned-status-earning-quick-rebuke-from-russia-1419339226 |date=2016-03-04 }}, [[The Wall Street journal]] (23 December 2014)</ref> that \"proved to be ineffective in guaranteeing Ukraine's security and protecting the country from external aggression and pressure\".<ref name=\"Xinhua 2014-12-24\">[http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/europe/europe/2014-12/24/c_133876007.htm Spotlight: Scrapping non-aligned status paves Ukraine's way to NATO, fuels Russia's wrath] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150406194902/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/europe/europe/2014-12/24/c_133876007.htm |date=2015-04-06 }}. [[Xinhua News Agency]]. Published on 2014-12-24.</ref> The Ukrainian military is since transforming to [[Standardization Agreement|NATO standards]].<ref name=iuyswbn /> [[Ukrainian Prime Minister]] [[Arseniy Yatsenyuk]] stated early February 2016 that de facto the Armed Forces must, soon as possible, begin its transition for Ukrainian entry into NATO and towards NATO-capable armed forces.<ref name=iuyswbn>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/323978.html Yatseniuk: Ukrainian army to switch to contract service, de facto become part of NATO] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160212083309/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/323978.html |date=2016-02-12 }}, [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (11 February 2016)</ref>\n\n== Organization ==\n[[File:Volodymyr Zelensky 2019 presidential inauguration 18.jpg|thumb|President [[Volodymyr Zelensky]] with the senior leadership of the Ukrainian military in May 2019]]\nIn late 2010 the total personnel (including 41,000 civilian workers) was 200,000.<ref>{{cite journal |title = Ukrainian Armed Forces 2009|page = 78|url = http://www.operationspaix.net/DATA/DOCUMENT/3081~v~White_Book_2009_-_Armed_Forces_of_Ukraine.pdf|accessdate = 22 October 2010<!--, 2010-->|archive-date = 9 February 2016|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160209211820/http://www.operationspaix.net/DATA/DOCUMENT/3081~v~White_Book_2009_-_Armed_Forces_of_Ukraine.pdf}}</ref>  Conscription was ended in October 2013;<ref name=\"upi.com\" /> at that time the Ukrainian armed forces were made up of 40% [[conscripts]] and 60% contract soldiers.<ref name=\"upi.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/Special/2013/10/03/Ukraine-to-end-military-conscription-after-autumn-call-ups/UPI-95521380772920/|title=Ukraine to end military conscription after autumn call-ups|access-date=2014-02-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140210024104/http://www.upi.com/Top_News/Special/2013/10/03/Ukraine-to-end-military-conscription-after-autumn-call-ups/UPI-95521380772920|archive-date=2014-02-10|url-status=live}}</ref> In April 2014 acting President [[Oleksandr Turchynov]] reinstated conscription in May 2014.<ref name=consback>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27247428 Ukraine reinstates conscription as crisis deepens] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821133617/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27247428 |date=2018-08-21 }}, [[BBC News]] (1 May 2014)</ref>\n\nUkraine has 130,000 personnel in its armed forces that could be boosted to about one million with reservists.<ref name=consback />\n\nThere is a reported total of 250,800 personnel in the Armed Forces in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title = Ukraine battles persist before cease-fire deadline; 25 dead|url = http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2015/feb/13/ukraine-battles-persist-ahead-cease-fire-deadline/|access-date = 2016-02-13|newspaper = [[Washington Times]]|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151226130136/http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2015/feb/13/ukraine-battles-persist-ahead-cease-fire-deadline/|archive-date = 2015-12-26|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nUkraine maintained until 2016 a number of [[Guards unit]]s, tracing their traditions to the [[Soviet Armed Forces]]. A list can be seen at [[List of guards units of Ukraine]]. There were reports in 2015 that all Guards units had been either disbanded or reformed to regular units,{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} this was proven false as all their Soviet decorations were removed from their titles and regimental colours by 15 November the same year due to the [[Decommunization in Ukraine|decommunization process in Ukraine]] which ceased promotion and glorification of the Soviet symbols. (On August 22, 2016, the Guards titles were removed from the unit titles.) Only one brigade, the 51st, a former Guards unit, had been dissolved the year before.\n\nFollowing the Russian aggression, Ukraine has adopted a new [[military doctrine]] (third edition) which made the Russian Federation its main opponent and announced Ukraine's intentions for closer relations with [[NATO]] armed services, most especially if it will join the organization in the future.<ref>[http://www.president.gov.ua/documents/5552015-19443 Ukase of the President of Ukraine #555/2015: About decision of the National Security and Defense Council of Ukraine of 2 September 2015 \"About new edition of the Ukrainian military doctrine\" (\u0423\u041a\u0410\u0417 \u041f\u0420\u0415\u0417\u0418\u0414\u0415\u041d\u0422\u0410 \u0423\u041a\u0420\u0410\u0407\u041d\u0418 \u2116555/2015: \u041f\u0440\u043e \u0440\u0456\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044f \u0420\u0430\u0434\u0438 \u043d\u0430\u0446\u0456\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0457 \u0431\u0435\u0437\u043f\u0435\u043a\u0438 \u0456 \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0438 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 \u0432\u0456\u0434 2 \u0432\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0441\u043d\u044f 2015 \u0440\u043e\u043a\u0443 \"\u041f\u0440\u043e \u043d\u043e\u0432\u0443 \u0440\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043a\u0446\u0456\u044e \u0412\u043e\u0454\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0457 \u0434\u043e\u043a\u0442\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0438 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438\")] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704003953/http://www.president.gov.ua/documents/5552015-19443 |date=4 July 2017 }}. [[President of Ukraine]].</ref>\n\n=== Chief of the General Staff ===\nThe [[Chief of the General Staff (Ukraine)|Chief of the General Staff]] oversees the Armed Forces of Ukraine.\n\n=== Ukrainian Ground Forces ===\n[[File:\u041f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u0442\u0435\u0445\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0438 - Equipment parade (29096544002).jpg|thumb|KRAZ Spartan]]\nAs of 2016, there were a reported 169,000 personnel in the [[Ukrainian Ground Forces]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tsn.ua/ukrayina/poltorak-postaviv-suhoputni-viyska-za-priklad-reform-v-ukrayini-845555.html|title=\u041f\u043e\u043b\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0430\u043a \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0432 \u0441\u0443\u0445\u043e\u043f\u0443\u0442\u043d\u0456 \u0432\u0456\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u0437\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u043a\u043b\u0430\u0434 \u0440\u0435\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c \u0432 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0456|date=13 December 2016|website=tsn.ua|accessdate=27 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301164523/https://tsn.ua/ukrayina/poltorak-postaviv-suhoputni-viyska-za-priklad-reform-v-ukrayini-845555.html|archive-date=1 March 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Ukrainian Ground Forces are divided into Armoured and [[Mechanized Infantry (Ukraine)|Mechanized Forces]], Army Aviation, Army Air Defence and [[Rocket Forces and Artillery (Ukraine)|Rocket and Artillery Troops]]. There are 13 mechanized brigades and two mountain warfare brigades in the Mechanized Forces. Ukraine also has two armoured brigades. There are seven rocket and artillery brigades as well as five airmobile brigades. Until 2013, the Ground Forces were divided into three army corps. These were disbanded in 2013 and reorganized as [[Operation Command West]], [[Operation Command North]] and [[Operation Command South]]. [[Operation Command East]] was formed in 2015 to coordinate forces in the War in Donbass.   [[File:Sukhoi Su-25 in Ukrainian service 269 n (cropped).jpg|thumb|Ukrainian Su-25]]\n\n=== Ukrainian Air Force ===\nIn 2016, the [[Ukrainian Air Force]] was reported to have included 36,300 personnel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mil.gov.ua/content/files/whitebook/WB_2013.pdf |title=\u0411\u0406\u041b\u0410 \u041a\u041d\u0418\u0413\u0410 2013 |website=Mil.gov.ua |accessdate=2017-01-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161130145304/http://www.mil.gov.ua/content/files/whitebook/WB_2013.pdf |archive-date=2016-11-30 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mil.gov.ua/index.php?part=white_book&lang=en |title=\u041c\u0456\u043d\u0456\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e &#124; \u041c\u0456\u043d\u0456\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0438 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 |website=Mil.gov.ua |date=2016-12-31 |accessdate=2017-01-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818092426/http://www.mil.gov.ua/index.php?part=white_book&lang=en |archive-date=2016-08-18 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Ukrainian Navy ===\n[[File:\u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e-\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0432\u0447\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044f \u201c\u0421\u0456 \u0411\u0440\u0438\u0437 - 2016\u201d (28075162974).jpg|thumb|The [[Krivak-class frigate|Krivak III-class]] frigate {{ship|Ukrainian frigate|Hetman Sahaydachniy|U130|2}}; the current flagship of the Ukrainian Navy<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.interfax.co.uk/ukraine-news/kozhara-hetman-sahaidachny-frigate-to-join-natos-anti-piracy-operation/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130917123531/http://www.interfax.co.uk/ukraine-news/kozhara-hetman-sahaidachny-frigate-to-join-natos-anti-piracy-operation/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=17 September 2013 |title=Kozhara: Hetman Sahaidachny frigate to join NATO's anti-piracy operation |newspaper=[[Interfax-Ukraine]] |date=17 September 2013}}</ref>]]\nAccording to an August 2015 ''[[Kyiv Post]]'' report, the [[Ukrainian Navy]] consisted of 6,500 personnel.<ref>{{Cite web| title=Ukraine's navy barely recovering from its near-death experience| url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/kyiv-post-plus/ukraines-navy-barely-recovering-from-its-near-death-experience-396689.html| accessdate=27 August 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150827214900/http://www.kyivpost.com/content/kyiv-post-plus/ukraines-navy-barely-recovering-from-its-near-death-experience-396689.html| archive-date=27 August 2015| url-status=live| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Air Assault and Airborne Forces ===\nThe [[Ukrainian Air Assault Forces]] are composed of 8 air assault brigades and support units.\n\n=== Special Forces ===\nUkraine's [[Special Forces of Ukraine|special forces]] are reported as 4,000 strong.<ref name=\"SF\" />\n\n=== Personnel and conscription ===\nThe Soviet Union required all able-bodied male citizens to serve two years in the armed forces (three years if drafted into the navy), although the draft could be postponed due to continued higher education. It was possible to be drafted into non Ministry of Defense military forces such as the [[Soviet Border Troops|KGB Border Guards]], the [[Militsiya]], or the [[Internal Troops]]. When Ukraine gained its independence it retained the policy of conscription, although the time in service was reduced to 18 months in the navy and one year in all other services. Ukraine also gradually began recruiting professional soldiers, although in almost all cases a person had to serve as a conscript prior to becoming a professional soldier. The [[Ukrainian Naval Infantry]] was the first service to convert to being staffed by fully professional marines.\n\nIn October 2013 President Yanukovich ended conscription in Ukraine, at the time 60% of Ukraine's forces were composed of professional soldiers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/Special/2013/10/03/Ukraine-to-end-military-conscription-after-autumn-call-ups/95521380772920/|publisher=UPI|title=Ukraine to end military conscription after autumn call-ups|access-date=2014-12-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141222231936/http://www.upi.com/Top_News/Special/2013/10/03/Ukraine-to-end-military-conscription-after-autumn-call-ups/95521380772920/|archive-date=2014-12-22|url-status=live}}</ref> However, due to the [[2014 Russian military intervention in Ukraine]] conscription, as well as a partial mobilization, was reinstated in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rferl.org/content/ukrainian-parliament-recommends-resumption-of-mandatory-conscription/25352661.html|publisher=Radio Free Europe|title=Ukrainian Parliament Recommends Resumption Of Mandatory Conscription|access-date=2014-12-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141222231128/http://www.rferl.org/content/ukrainian-parliament-recommends-resumption-of-mandatory-conscription/25352661.html|archive-date=2014-12-22|url-status=live}}</ref> Ukraine has modified the age group of males eligible for conscription for 2015 from 18-25 to the 20-27 age group.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/12/20/us-ukraine-crisis-military-idUSKBN0JY0K620141220|publisher=reuters|title=Ukraine to spend five percent of 2015 budget on defense and security|access-date=2017-06-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924211714/http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/12/20/us-ukraine-crisis-military-idUSKBN0JY0K620141220|archive-date=2015-09-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter serving out the term of service Ukraine's conscripts become part of the inactive reserve and are eligible to be recalled for mobilization until they reach age 55, age 60 for officers. Due to the [[War in Donbass]] Ukraine has instated a partial mobilization to fill needed positions in its armed forces, recalling conscripts who have served before, because of the war many conscripts have also been forced to serve longer than their original 18-month term of service.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kiev1.org/en/zakonoproekt-pro-chastichnuyu-mobilizatsiyu-4320.html|publisher=[[Kiev]]1|title=Draft law No. 4320 and Decree No. 607 on partial mobilization full text|access-date=2014-12-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223010652/http://kiev1.org/en/zakonoproekt-pro-chastichnuyu-mobilizatsiyu-4320.html|archive-date=2014-12-23|url-status=dead}}</ref> It was planned that in 2015 Ukraine would undergo three waves of partial mobilization, this would have allowed new troops to replace those serving longer than their original term of service.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/turchynov-ukraine-to-see-three-waves-of-mobilization-in-2015-375869.html|newspaper=Kyiv Post|title=Turchynov: Ukraine to see three waves of mobilization in 2015|access-date=2014-12-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141222234712/https://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/turchynov-ukraine-to-see-three-waves-of-mobilization-in-2015-375869.html|archive-date=2014-12-22|url-status=live}}</ref> As a result, the number of defections from Ukrainian Armed Forces has risen substantially cause the Ukrainian conscripts had no wish to put their life at risk in combat. An advisor of Ukrainian president described the quality of forcibly mobilized Ukrainian soldiers as \"alcoholics and dodgers, drug addicts and morons\".<ref>{{cite book |last=Andrews |first=John |date=2016 |title=The World in Conflict: Understanding the world's troublespots |isbn=978-1-78283-115-0 |publisher=Profile Books |url=https://books.google.com/?id=00GkCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT197&lpg=PT197&dq=%22alcoholics+and+dodgers,+drug+addicts+and+morons.%22#v=onepage&q=%22alcoholics%20and%20dodgers%2C%20drug%20addicts%20and%20morons.%22&f=false |access-date=2018-06-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625103704/https://books.google.ca/books?id=00GkCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT197&lpg=PT197&dq=%22alcoholics+and+dodgers,+drug+addicts+and+morons.%22&source=bl&ots=eKeI0M_ZZf&sig=u8M76Zn-OG2PLTJKLxh8LOt2VwU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwibjeP7pP_TAhVn5IMKHZwQBi8Q6AEIOjAB#v=onepage&q=%22alcoholics%20and%20dodgers%2C%20drug%20addicts%20and%20morons.%22&f=false |archive-date=2018-06-25 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to many reports the increased consumption of drugs and alcohol on duty has become a serious issue in Ukrainian Armed Forces. As a response the Ukrainian government launched a military police service and deployed National Guards in war zone.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ponomarenko. |first1=Illia |title=Ukraine to create true military police force in 2017 |url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/ukraine-create-reformed-military-police-2017.html |website=Kyiv Post |accessdate=25 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170712164040/https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/ukraine-create-reformed-military-police-2017.html |archive-date=12 July 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Ukraine and Russia are both trapped by the war in Donbas |url=https://www.economist.com/europe/2017/05/25/ukraine-and-russia-are-both-trapped-by-the-war-in-donbas |website=The Economist |accessdate=25 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625213517/https://www.economist.com/europe/2017/05/25/ukraine-and-russia-are-both-trapped-by-the-war-in-donbas |archive-date=25 June 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=ATO fighter: Our first enemy is separatists, the second one is Ukrainian top command, and the third one is alcohol, it is impossible to fight against it |url=http://english.gordonua.com/news/exclusiveenglish/ato-53971.html |website=english.gordonua.com |accessdate=25 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180626001432/http://english.gordonua.com/news/exclusiveenglish/ato-53971.html |archive-date=26 June 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nDue to the reintroduction of conscription, and partial mobilization, Ukraine's armed forces is expected to nearly double from approximately 130,000 personnel in December 2014 to approximately 250,000 personnel in 2015.\n\nAll medical workers in Ukraine, regardless of gender, are eligible to be called up for service in case of a national emergency.\n\n[[Draft dodging]] is present in Ukraine as with most nations using the draft. It was reported that between April and August 2014, over 1,000 criminal inquires into draft evasion were opened in Ukraine.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.interfax.com/newsinf.asp?id=529597 |publisher= Interfax |title= Over 1000 criminal inquires opened into draft evasion cases. |access-date= 2014-12-23 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141223084548/http://www.interfax.com/newsinf.asp?id=529597 |archive-date= 2014-12-23 |url-status= live }}</ref> Draft evasion can be problematic because unless a male citizen was unable to serve for medical reasons, an application to receive an international passport of Ukraine may be denied due to a lack of military service, thus preventing the individual from traveling abroad.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://zagranpasport.cn.ua/poluchenie-zagranpasporta-v-ukraine |trans-title= Passport Service of Ukraine |title= \u041f\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0437\u0430\u0433\u0440\u0430\u043d\u043f\u0430\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0432 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0435 |access-date= 2014-12-23 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150409022437/http://zagranpasport.cn.ua/poluchenie-zagranpasporta-v-ukraine |archive-date= 2015-04-09 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\nAs of autumn 2016, conscripts were no longer deployed in the so-called [[ATO zone|\"ATO\"-operations]] in the east of Ukraine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unian.info/society/1540546-poroshenko-signs-decree-on-demobilization-of-sixth-wave-of-ukraine-troops.html|title=Poroshenko signs decree on demobilization of sixth wave of Ukraine troops|access-date=2016-10-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161031164847/http://www.unian.info/society/1540546-poroshenko-signs-decree-on-demobilization-of-sixth-wave-of-ukraine-troops.html|archive-date=2016-10-31|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Contract Service ===\nIn 2017 more than 14 thousand people signed up for contract service with the Armed Forces.<ref name=UA30517 />\n\nFor participating in the [[War in Donbass]]  (in May 2017 7.5 thousand) soldiers on the front line receive an average salary of 16 thousand [[Ukrainian Hryvnia]].<ref name=UA30517 /> The minimum maintenance for a contract soldier is 7000 Hryvnia.<ref name=UA30517 />\n\n[[West Ukraine]] supplies the fewest people for contract service.<ref name=UA30517>{{in lang|uk}} [http://pda.pravda.com.ua/news/id_7145423 The Defense Ministry told which areas of shortage of recruits] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608144546/http://pda.pravda.com.ua/news/id_7145423 |date=2017-06-08 }}, [[Ukrayinska Pravda]] (30 May 2017)</ref>\n\n=== Paramilitary Forces ===\nUkraine's Armed Forces outside the jurisdiction of the [[Ministry of Defense (Ukraine)|Ministry of Defense]] consist of:\n\n* [[Internal Troops of Ukraine|Internal Troops]] \u2192 [[National Guard of Ukraine|National Guard]] ([[Ministry of Internal Affairs (Ukraine)|Ministry of Internal Affairs]]): 46,000 <ref name=\"Archived copy\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.unian.info/society/1474054-avakov-announces-large-scale-cleansing-among-generals.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-11-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823174230/https://www.unian.info/society/1474054-avakov-announces-large-scale-cleansing-among-generals.html |archive-date=2018-08-23 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n** Special operation formations of the Ministry of Internal Affairs, i.e. Omega, Scorpion (nuclear sites security), Tytan, and others. Most of Felidae-named formations (such as Bars, Jaguar, others) along with Berkut were reformed.\n* [[State Border Guard Service of Ukraine|Border Guard]]: 42,000 (including 8,000 civilian workers)<ref name=\"Archived copy\"/> \n** [[Ukrainian Sea Guard]] \u2013 the [[coast guard]] within the State Border Guard Service of Ukraine\n* Various military troops of the [[Security Service of Ukraine|SBU]] (no generic name): 30,000\n* Civil Defence Forces ([[State Emergency Service of Ukraine]]): 10,218 (including 668 civilian workers)<ref>{{in lang|uk}} [http://zakon1.rada.gov.ua/cgi-bin/laws/main.cgi?nreg=328-14 Law of Ukraine about structure of Civil Defence Forces 22 December 1998 \u2116 328-XIV]</ref>\n* [[Special Transportation Service of Ukraine]] \u2013 (Ministry of Transportation and Communications)<ref>{{in lang|uk}} [http://zakon.rada.gov.ua/cgi-bin/laws/main.cgi?nreg=1449-15 Law of Ukraine about Special Transportation Service of Ukraine 5 February 2004 \u2116 1449-IV]</ref>\n\nAlthough not components of the Armed Forces, these militarized institutions are supposed to come under the Armed Forces' command during [[war]]time.\n\n=== Role of women ===\nOn 3 June 2016, Defense Ministry's Order No. 292 allowed women to serve in combat units.<ref name=waiUm3616 />\n\nAccording to Defense Ministry figures early June 2016 some 49,500 women served in and worked in the Ukrainian military; more than 17,000 were military servicewomen, of which more than 2,000 officers.<ref name=waiUm3616 /> Women have also joined the various volunteer [[Territorial defense battalion (Ukraine)|Territorial defense battalions]] before the order for women's integration in the armed forces was enacted.<ref name=waiUm3616 /> Women are eligible to be drafted into the military as officers.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Ukraine to Call Up Women Over 20 for Armed Forces|url = http://europe.newsweek.com/ukraine-armed-forces-set-call-female-citizens-aged-20-50-new-recruitment-cycle-304276?rx=us|website = Newsweek|access-date = 2016-02-09|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20161008132731/http://europe.newsweek.com/ukraine-armed-forces-set-call-female-citizens-aged-20-50-new-recruitment-cycle-304276?rx=us|archive-date = 2016-10-08|url-status = live}}</ref> In 2009 women comprised almost 13% of the armed forces (18,000 personnel) but with few females holding high rank (2.9% or 1,202 women).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = UNDP helps Ukrainian Ministry of Defence create new opportunities for women|url = http://www.undp.org.ua/en/media/41-democratic-governance/814-undp-helps-ukrainian-ministry-of-defence-create-new-opportunities-for-women|date = 16 June 2009|access-date = 26 June 2009|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090626102048/http://www.undp.org.ua/en/media/41-democratic-governance/814-undp-helps-ukrainian-ministry-of-defence-create-new-opportunities-for-women|archive-date = 26 June 2009}}</ref> Contractual military service accounted for almost 44% of women. However, this being closely linked to the low salary of such positions: men refuse to serve in these conditions while women accept them.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[Nadiya Savchenko]] is perhaps one of the most well known female Ukrainian soldiers and was held as a prisoner in Russia from July 2014 until May 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/defense-team-intends-to-seek-pow-status-for-ukrainian-pilot-savchenko-370987.html|newspaper=Kyiv Post|title=Defense team intends to seek POW status for Ukrainian pilot Savchenko|access-date=2014-12-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223081925/http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/defense-team-intends-to-seek-pow-status-for-ukrainian-pilot-savchenko-370987.html|archive-date=2014-12-23|url-status=live}}<br />{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-36378173 |title=Russia 'frees Ukraine pilot Savchenko in prisoner swap' |date=2016-05-25 |access-date=2016-05-25 |publisher=BBC |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160525131556/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-36378173 |archive-date=2016-05-25 |url-status=live }}<br />{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28232966 |title= Ukraine conflict: Russia charges pilot over deaths |work= [[BBC News]] |date= 9 July 2014 |access-date= 21 June 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180305010137/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28232966 |archive-date= 5 March 2018 |url-status= live |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[President of Ukraine|President]] [[Petro Poroshenko]], in October 2016 about ten thousand women served in combat units.<ref>[http://www.unian.info/society/1572377-poroshenko-congratulates-ukrainian-defenders-tells-how-many-soldiers-killed-in-donbas.html Poroshenko congratulates Ukrainian defenders, tells how many soldiers killed in Donbas] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018191922/http://www.unian.info/society/1572377-poroshenko-congratulates-ukrainian-defenders-tells-how-many-soldiers-killed-in-donbas.html |date=2016-10-18 }}, [[UNIAN]] (14 October 2016)</ref>\n\nIn September 2018 legislation made women and men equal in the military and law enforcement agencies.<ref name=\"1stUkrainianFemaleGeneral\"/> The following month [[Liudmyla Shugaley]] became Ukraine's first female general (she was appointed the head of the Military Medical Directorate of the [[Security Service of Ukraine]]).<ref name=\"1stUkrainianFemaleGeneral\">[https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/ukraine-appoints-its-first-female-general.html Ukraine appoints its first female general], [[Kyiv Post]] (14 October 2018)</ref>\n\n== Education and schools ==\nA number of universities have specialized military institutes, such as the Faculty of Military Legal Studies at Kharkiv's [[National Yaroslav Mudryi Law Academy]] of Ukraine. The primary Ukrainian military academies are:\n* [[Hetman Petro Sahaidachnyi National Ground Forces Academy]], [[Lviv]]\n* [[Nakhimov Higher Naval Institute (Sevastopol)|Admiral Pavel Nakhimov Naval Academy]], [[Sevastopol]]\n** transferred to [[Mykolaiv]]\n* [[Ivan Kozhedub National Air Force University]], [[Kharkiv]]\n\nIn addition the [[Ivan Chernyakhovsky National Defense University of Ukraine]] is in [[Kiev]].<ref>{{in lang|uk}} [http://www.nuou.org.ua/ Official website of National Defense University of Ukraine] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131226014025/http://nuou.org.ua/ |date=2013-12-26 }}</ref>\n\nThe Central Hospital of the Armed Forces is located in [[Kiev]].<ref>{{Cite web|script-title=uk:\u0406\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0456\u044f \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0443|url=http://gvkg.kiev.ua/index.php/histori|website=gvkg.kiev.ua|access-date=2016-02-13|language=uk, English|trans-title=History of the Centre|publisher=National Military Main Medical Clinical Center|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160213214415/http://gvkg.kiev.ua/index.php/histori|archive-date=13 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe armed forces' military high school is located in [[Kiev]] \u2013 the [[Ivan Bohun Military High School]].\n\n== Recent operations ==\n[[File:Members of the Ukrainian Army\u2019s 19th CBRN-Battalion maintaining decontamination skills in Support of Operation Iraqi Freedom at Camp Arifjan, in KUWAIT on August 3rd 2003.jpg|thumb|Members of the Ukrainian Army's 19th Nuclear, Biological and Chemical Battalion in Kuwait]]\nUkraine has been playing an increasingly larger role in peacekeeping operations. Since 1992, over 30,000 soldiers have taken part in missions in the former Yugoslavia ([[IFOR]] in [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[UNPROFOR]] and [[UNTAES]] in [[Croatia]], [[KFor]] in [[Kosovo]]), the Middle East ([[Southern Lebanon]], [[Kuwait]], [[Iraq]]), and Africa ([[Angola]], [[Sierra Leone]], [[Liberia]]).<ref name=\"UP\" />\n[[File:\u041c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0447\u0456 \u043c\u0456\u0441\u0456\u0457 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438.png|thumb|Deployments outside Ukraine since 1991]]\nSince 1997, Ukraine has been working closely with NATO and especially with Poland. A Ukrainian unit was deployed as part of the multinational force in Iraq under [[Poland|Polish]] command. Ukrainian troops are also deployed as part of the [[Polish-Ukrainian Peace Force Battalion|Ukrainian-Polish Battalion (UKRPOLBAT)]] in Kosovo. The total Ukrainian military deployment around the world as of 1 August 2009 was 540 servicemen participating in 8 peacekeeping missions.<ref name=UP>{{cite web|url=http://www.mil.gov.ua/index.php?part=peacekeeping&lang=en|title=\u041c\u0456\u043d\u0456\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e|access-date=2008-04-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011104812/http://www.mil.gov.ua/index.php?part=peacekeeping&lang=en|archive-date=2007-10-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe first battle of a regular formation of the Ukrainian Armed Forces happened on April 6, 2004 in [[Kut]], [[Iraq]], when the Ukrainian peacekeeping contingent was attacked by militants of the [[Mahdi Army]]. The Ukrainians took fire, and over several hours held the objectives they had been assigned to secure.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.meforum.org/article/669|title=Al-Kut, Iraq: After-Battle Report|date=1 September 2004|journal=Middle East Quarterly|access-date=10 April 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517044004/http://www.meforum.org/article/669|archive-date=17 May 2008|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ukrainian military in Iraq.jpg|thumb|left|Ukrainian troops riding alongside US Marines in Iraq]]Ukrainian troops as part of the former Soviet Armed Forces contingent participated in [[UNPROFOR]] in 1992, and in the summer of that year were involved into the civil war in [[Yugoslavia]]. On July 3, 1992 the [[Verkhovna Rada]] adopted a resolution committing the Ukrainian Armed Forces to UN peacekeeping missions. The [[Ministry of Defense (Ukraine)|Minister of Defense]], [[Kostyantyn Morozov]], ordered the creation of the 240th Separate Special Battalion (UKRBAT-1) which was based on the [[93rd Guards Motor Rifle Division]] (now the [[93rd Mechanized Brigade (Ukraine)|93rd Mechanized Brigade]]). Soon after arrival in [[Sarajevo]] on July 31, 1992, the battalion's artillery ended up in the middle of a mutual mortar fight between the Bosnian Serbs and Bosnian Muslims. One of the Serbian shells hit the Ukrainian position, seriously wounding seven soldiers, one of whom died after hospitalization in Germany.\n\nSince gaining independence Ukraine has deployed troops to Iraq, Afghanistan, Kosovo, as well as dedicating peacekeepers to UN missions to Africa (including helicopter units). Ukrainian naval units also participated in anti piracy operations off the coast of Somalia prior to being recalled due to the [[2014 Russian intervention in Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://eunavfor.eu/eu-naval-force-admiral-visits-ukrainian-navy-warship-hetman-sagaidachny/|title=EU Naval Force Admiral Visits Ukrainian Navy Warship Hetman Sagaidachny|date=18 Dec 2013|access-date=19 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221030925/http://eunavfor.eu/eu-naval-force-admiral-visits-ukrainian-navy-warship-hetman-sagaidachny/|archive-date=21 February 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 January 2015 Ukraine's 18th separate helicopter detachment along with other [[MONUSCO]] troops carried out a successful operation eliminating 2 camps belonging to illegal armed groups in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://army.unian.net/1033527-ukrainskiy-kontingent-uchastvuet-v-operatsiyah-protiv-bandformirovaniy-v-kongo.html|publisher=unian|title=\u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0442 \u0443\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0443\u0435\u0442 \u0432 \u043e\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f\u0445 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0442\u0438\u0432 \u0431\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0432 \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0433\u043e \u041f\u043e\u0434\u0440\u043e\u0431\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0447\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0439\u0442\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0423\u041d\u0418\u0410\u041d|access-date=2015-01-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150126091147/http://army.unian.net/1033527-ukrainskiy-kontingent-uchastvuet-v-operatsiyah-protiv-bandformirovaniy-v-kongo.html|archive-date=2015-01-26|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Deployment outside Ukraine ===\n\n* {{flag|Afghanistan}}: [[International Security Assistance Force|ISAF]] (PRT CHAGHCHARAN) \u2013 13 Officers (3 medical officers)<ref name=\"UP\" />\n* {{flag|Democratic Republic of the Congo}}: ([[United Nations Mission in the Democratic Republic of Congo|MONUSCO]]) \u2013 12 Experts on Mission and four [[Mi-24]] helicopters<ref name=\"UP\" /><ref name=UN1>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/en/peacekeeping/contributors/2010/sept10_5.pdf|title=UN Mission's Contributions by Country for September 2010|access-date=2017-06-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170321050227/http://www.un.org/en/peacekeeping/contributors/2010/sept10_5.pdf|archive-date=2017-03-21|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"un-20120307\">{{cite news |url=https://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=41480 |title=DR Congo: UN peacekeeping mission receives tactical helicopters from Ukraine |newspaper=UN Daily News |date=7 March 2012 |accessdate=18 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529210703/http://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=41480 |archive-date=29 May 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"nbc-20140514\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/ukraine-crisis/helicopter-may-land-ukraines-military-hot-water-u-n-n105041 |title=Helicopter May Land Ukraine's Military in Hot Water With U.N. |author=Alexander Smith |publisher=NBC News |date=14 May 2014 |accessdate=18 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529015705/http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/ukraine-crisis/helicopter-may-land-ukraines-military-hot-water-u-n-n105041 |archive-date=29 May 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* {{flag|Iraq}} ([[NATO Training Mission \u2013 Iraq|NTM-I]]): \u2013 10 officers<ref name=\"UP\" /><ref>[http://www.afsouth.nato.int/JFCN_Missions/NTM-I/Factsheets/NTMI_part.htm Participating nations] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927190220/http://www.afsouth.nato.int/JFCN_Missions/NTM-I/Factsheets/NTMI_part.htm |date=2011-09-27 }}</ref>\n* {{flag|Kosovo}}: ([[Kosovo Force|KFOR]]) \u2013 128 Soldiers<ref name=\"UP\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/kfor/structur/nations/placemap/kfor_placemat.pdf|title=KFOR Troops (Placemat)|access-date=2009-09-28|archive-url=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20091005182919/http://www.nato.int/kfor/structur/nations/placemap/kfor_placemat.pdf|archive-date=2009-10-05|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Kosovo}}: ([[United Nations Interim Administration Mission in Kosovo|UNMIK]]) \u2013 1 Military Liaison Component Chief of Staff, 1 liaison officer<ref name=\"UP\" /><ref name=\"UN1\" />\n* {{flag|Liberia}}: ([[United Nations Mission in Liberia|UNMIL]]) \u2013 277 Contingent Troops, 2 Experts on Mission<ref name=\"UP\" /><ref name=\"UN1\" />\n* {{flag|Moldova}}: ([[Transnistria]]) \u2013 10 Military Observers<ref name=\"UP\" />\n* {{flag|Sudan}}: ([[United Nations Mission in Sudan|UNMIS]]) \u2013 9 Experts on Mission<ref name=\"UP\" /><ref name=\"UN1\" />\n* {{flagcountry|Mali}} (20)\n\n=== 2014 Crimean crisis ===\n{{Main|Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation}}\nOn 2 March 2014, the Ukrainian Armed Forces were placed on full alert following a Russian military intervention in [[Crimean Peninsula|Crimea]].<ref name=NYT>{{cite web|last=Erlanger|first=Steven|title=Ukrainian Government Rushes to Dampen Secessionist Sentiment|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/03/world/europe/ukraine.html|work=New York Times|accessdate=3 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140302220803/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/03/world/europe/ukraine.html|archive-date=2 March 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March 2014, Ukraine drew plans to withdraw all its troops and their families to the mainland \"quickly and efficiently\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-26656617|title=Ukraine 'preparing withdrawal of troops from Crimea'|work=BBC News|accessdate=19 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140319214718/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-26656617|archive-date=19 March 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Traditions ==\n[[File:\u041a\u0438\u0457\u0432, \u0413\u0440\u0443\u0448\u0435\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0439\u043b\u0430 \u0432\u0443\u043b. 30, \u0411\u0443\u0434\u0438\u043d\u043e\u043a \u0412\u0456\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0457 \u0448\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0438.jpg|thumb|The [[Central House of Officers of the Armed Forces of Ukraine]].]]\n*On 9 August 2018, President [[Petro Poroshenko]] announced that the [[Battle cry]] ''[[Glory to Ukraine]]'' will be the official greeting of the armed forces, replacing the Soviet era military greeting of ''Hello Comrades'' (''\u0412\u0456\u0442\u0430\u044e \u0442\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0448\u0456'', ''Vitayu tovaryshi'').<ref>{{cite web |last1=Poroshenko |first1=Petro |title=President: The words \"Glory to Ukraine! Glory to the Heroes!\" will be the official greetings of the Armed Forces of our state |url=https://www.president.gov.ua/en/news/prezident-slova-slava-ukrayini-geroyam-slava-budut-oficijnim-48938 |website=PRESIDENT OF UKRAINE Official website |publisher=Government of Ukraine |accessdate=11 August 2018}}</ref> The greeting was first used during the [[Kiev Independence Day Parade]] that year celebrating the [[centennial]] of the Ukrainian state.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ukrainianweek.com/BreakingNews/218751|title=Ukraine's Independence Day military parade in Kyiv|website= |publisher=[[The Ukrainian Week]] |accessdate=24 August 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://112.international/ukraine-top-news/verkhovna-rada-approves-military-salute-glory-to-ukraine-31882.html Verkhovna Rada approves military salute \u2018Glory to Ukraine!\u2019], [[112 Ukraine]] (6 September 2018)<br>[https://www.unian.info/politics/10285848-ukraine-s-parliament-approves-new-army-police-greeting.html Ukraine's parliament approves new army, police greeting], [[UNIAN]] (4 October 2018)</ref> It is also the official greeting of the [[National Police of Ukraine]].<ref name=\"interfaxua535728\">[https://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/535728.html Rada approves salute 'Glory to Ukraine' in Ukrainian army], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (4 October 2018)</ref>\n*The [[Central House of Officers of the Armed Forces of Ukraine]] is the [[cultural center]] of the Ukrainian military located in [[Kiev]]. Since its recent reorganization, it has become one of the leading cultural centers in the Ukrainian capital. It served as a concert hall for military officers in the [[Aftermath of World War II|post-war]] years, during which the whole city of Kyiv was in ruins and there were practically no audience halls.  It has hosted the National Military History Museum since October 1995.<ref>http://mesta.kiev.ua/museums/page/7</ref>\n\n*The Ukrainian Army unveiled its current uniform on Independence Day in 2016.<ref name=\"nuUaWP\"/> The new uniforms were modeled on British and Polish military styles<ref name=\"nuUaWP\"/> and incorporate details from the uniforms worn by the [[Ukrainian People's Army]].<ref name=\"nuUaWP\">[http://m.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/aug/25/fashion-statement-ukrainian-troops-debut-post-sovi/ Fashion statement: Ukrainian troops debut post-Soviet uniforms] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829230710/http://m.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/aug/25/fashion-statement-ukrainian-troops-debut-post-sovi/ |date=2016-08-29 }}, [[The Washington Times]] (25 August 2016)</ref> The cap includes an insignia of a [[Ukrainian Cossack]] grasping a cross.<ref name=\"nuUaWP\"/> Although mainly designed for the ground forces, other branches based their new uniforms off of the update. Prior to 2016, the uniforms were based on the Soviet military precedent.\n*The military uses the Soviet [[goose step|goosestep]] (originally used by [[Prussia]] under the orders of King [[Frederick the Great]]) with the speed of the step being 75 steps per minute and elements of the marching pace of the [[Sich Riflemen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.segodnya.ua/ukraine/ukrainckie-coldaty-budut-zadirat-nohi-na-5-cm-nizhe.html|script-title=uk:\u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0441\u043e\u043b\u0434\u0430\u0442\u044b \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0443\u0442 \u0437\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0440\u0430\u0442\u044c \u043d\u043e\u0433\u0438 \u043d\u0430 5 \u0441\u043c \u043d\u0438\u0436\u0435|author=\u0411\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434|date=15 December 2009|website=[[\u0421\u0435\u0433\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044f (\u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430, \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0430)|\u0427\u0410\u041e \"\u0421\u0435\u0433\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044f \u041c\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0438\u043c\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0430\"]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mignews.com.ua/sobitiya/inukraine/2349968.html|script-title=uk:\"\u041d\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439\" \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u0448\u0430\u0433 \u0441\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0443\u044e \u0430\u0440\u043c\u0438\u044e \u044d\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0439 |date=25 February 2010|website=MIGnews}}</ref>\n*When in the [[present arms (command)|present arms]] position, all unit colors are requred to dip.\n*The S. Tvorun arrangement of the ''[[Zaporizhian March]]'' has been used in the ZSU since 1991 when it replaced ''[[Farewell of Slavianka]]'' in being performed during recruiting days, when new servicemen are welcomed to the Armed Forces and recite their enlistment oaths.\n\n== Budget ==\nUkraine's National Security Strategy foresees that its National Security and Defense budget should be at least 5% of Ukraine's GDP.<ref name=pS17Udb>[https://www.unian.info/economics/2134511-ukraine-to-allocate-63-bln-for-security-defense-in-2018-poroshenko.html Ukraine to allocate $6.3 bln for security, defense in 2018 \u2013 Poroshenko] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914215920/https://www.unian.info/economics/2134511-ukraine-to-allocate-63-bln-for-security-defense-in-2018-poroshenko.html |date=2017-09-14 }}, [[UNIAN]] (14 September 2017)<br />{{in lang|uk}} [http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2017/12/7/7164746/ Parliament approved the 2018 state budget] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103020443/http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2017/12/7/7164746/ |date=2018-01-03 }}, [[Ukrayinska Pravda]] (7 December 2017)</ref>\n\nOn 21 December 2016 the [[Ukrainian parliament]] adopted its 2017 National Security and Defense budget worth $5.172 billion; that being 5% of Ukraine's [[GDP]]. In 2016 defense expenditures amounted to $4.4 billion in 2016, or 5% of the GDP.<ref name=JbUa16>[http://www.janes.com/article/56428/ukrainian-military-budget-to-reduce-likelihood-of-separatist-attacks-in-donetsk-and-luhansk-improve-infrastructure-security Ukrainian military budget to reduce likelihood of separatist attacks in Donetsk and Luhansk, improve infrastructure security] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160301024720/http://www.janes.com/article/56428/ukrainian-military-budget-to-reduce-likelihood-of-separatist-attacks-in-donetsk-and-luhansk-improve-infrastructure-security |date=2016-03-01 }}, [[IHS Jane's 360]] (2 December 2015)</ref><ref name=JbUa162>[http://www.unian.info/economics/1466853-ukraine-to-spend-3-of-gdp-on-defense-in-2017-finance-minister.htmlUkraine to spend 3% of GDP on defense in 2017: Finance minister]{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [[UNIAN]] (13 August 2016)</ref> This (2016 figure) was a 23% increase from 2013 and a 65% increase from 2005.<ref name=JbUa16 /> From the total, 60% was budgeted to be spent on defence and 40% on security and policing.<ref name=JbUa16 /> 2016 also saw a 30% increase in weapons development spending.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uatoday.tv/politics/ukraine-to-increase-military-expenditure-by-30-in-2016-548205.html|title=UNIAN News. Latest news of Ukraine and world|website=uatoday.tv|access-date=2016-03-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160319202016/http://uatoday.tv/politics/ukraine-to-increase-military-expenditure-by-30-in-2016-548205.html|archive-date=2016-03-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Corruption in Ukraine|Corruption]], which was practically institutionalized in Ukraine, combined with small budgets left the military in such a depleted condition that their ability to confront the crisis in Crimea and the Donbass was minimal. All Ukrainian defence sector is heavily affected by the systemic corruption which is hindering its capacity to perform the tasks of national security. In addition, it is also undermines popular trust in the military as an institution. Despite a great number of efforts to resolve the issue there are signs that enough is not being done.<ref>Adriana Lins de Albuquerque and Jakob Hedenskog [https://www.foi.se/report-search/pdf?fileName=D%3A%5CReportSearch%5CFiles%5C78b12d4c-19d6-4727-b96b-7faa5ba088dc.pdf Ukraine A Defence Sector Reform Assessment] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201044616/https://www.foi.se/report-search/pdf?fileName=D:%5CReportSearch%5CFiles%5C78b12d4c-19d6-4727-b96b-7faa5ba088dc.pdf |date=2017-12-01 }} FOI-R-4157-SE</ref>\n\nUkrainian government has launched major structural reforms of the army to meet NATO standards by 2020, but not too many believe that it can successfully meet a deadline. Most part of the problems remain intact, for example: lack of civilian and parliamentary control of the armed forces, lack of internal coordination between different departments, poor integration of volunteers into the regular army, impunity and abusive behavior of military personnel in the conflict zone and systemic corruption and nontransparency of financial resources, especially in the Ukroboronprom defense-industry monopoly.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://carnegieendowment.org/2018/02/22/ukraine-s-toughest-fight-challenge-of-military-reform-pub-75609 |title=Ukraine's Toughest Fight: The Challenge of Military Reform |access-date=2018-10-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181003014204/https://carnegieendowment.org/2018/02/22/ukraine-s-toughest-fight-challenge-of-military-reform-pub-75609 |archive-date=2018-10-03 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 the military budget has grown dramatically, to nearly 5% of GDP. Corruption remains a serious problem operating at all levels of Ukrainian society, and the lack of modern military organizational structure has confounded efforts at reform.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/19/world/europe/ukraine-corruption-military.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-04-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180415125144/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/19/world/europe/ukraine-corruption-military.html |archive-date=2018-04-15 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Budget per year (Defense budget only, not \"Security and Defense\" combined) ===\n*2003: $1.01 Billion (UAH 5.06 billion @5.0 exchange rate)<ref name=\"pidruchniki.com\">https://pidruchniki.com/16011013/finansi/sklad_struktura_vidatkiv_derzhavnogo_byudzhetu_ukrayini</ref>\n*2004: $1.29 Billion (UAH 6.46 billion @5.0 exchange rate)<ref name=\"pidruchniki.com\"/>\n*2005: $1.23 Billion (UAH 6.16 billion @5.0 exchange rate)<ref name=\"pidruchniki.com\"/>\n*2006: $1.47 Billion (UAH 7.35 billion @5.0 exchange rate)<ref name=\"pidruchniki.com\"/>\n*2007: $2.12 Billion (UAH 10.6 billion @5.0 exchange rate)<ref name=\"pidruchniki.com\"/>\n*2008: $1.78 Billion (UAH 8.926 billion @5.0 exchange rate)<ref name=\"zakon.rada.gov.ua\">https://zakon.rada.gov.ua/laws/show/107-17</ref>\n*2009: $0.93 Billion (UAH 7.4 billion @8.0 exchange rate)<ref name=\"tyzhden.ua\">https://tyzhden.ua/Publication/2322</ref>\n*2010: $1.63 Billion (UAH 13.1 billion @8.0 exchange rate)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pravda.com.ua/articles/2009/09/29/4211736/|title=\u042f\u043a \u0422\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u0437\u0430\u043a\u0440\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u0440\u043e\u0442\u0438 \u0433\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u0430\u043c|access-date=2019-12-02|trans-title=How Tymoshenko closed her mouth to the generals|website=pravda.com.ua|date=2009-09-29|author=\u0410\u041d\u041d\u0410 \u0411\u0410\u0411\u0406\u041d\u0415\u0426\u042c}}</ref>\n*2011: $1.82 Billion (UAH 14.6 billion @8.0 exchange rate)<ref name=\"vkurse.ua\">http://vkurse.ua/ua/society/stimulirovat-voennykh-premiyami.html</ref>\n*2012: $2.05 Billion (UAH 16.4 billion @8.0 exchange rate)<ref name=\"economy.nayka.com.ua\">http://www.economy.nayka.com.ua/?op=1&z=922</ref>\n*2013: $1.88 Billion (UAH 15.3 billion @8.1 exchange rate)  <ref name=\"news.finance.ua\">https://news.finance.ua/ru/news/-/293024/voennye-rashody-ukrainy-v-2013-godu-uvelicheny-na-1-15-minfin</ref>\n*2014: $1.37 Billion (UAH 15.1 billion @11.0 exchange rate) <ref name=\"bbc.com\">https://www.bbc.com/ukrainian/business/2014/12/141224_budget_spendings_project-2015_vc</ref>\n*2015: $1.91 Billion (UAH 40.2 billion @21.0 exchange rate) <ref name=\"bbc.com\"/>\n*2016: $2.11 Billion (UAH 56 billion) <ref name=\"depo.ua\">https://www.depo.ua/ukr/war/proekt-viyskovogo-byudzhetu-2017---skilki-kudi-y-navishcho-26092016090000</ref>\n*2017: $2.65 Billion (UAH 69 billion) <ref name=\"mil.in.ua\">https://mil.in.ua/uk/d0-b1-d1-8e-d0-b4-d0-b6-d0-b5-d1-82-d1-96-2019-d0-bd-d0-b0-d0-be-d0-b1-d0-be-d1-80-d0-be-d0-bd-d1-83-d0-bf-d0-b5-d1-80-d0-b5-d0-b4-d0-b1-d0-b0-d1-87-d0-b5-d0-bd-d0-be-538-d0-b2-d0-b2-d0-bf/</ref>\n*2018: $3.20 Billion (UAH 83.3 billion) <ref name=\"mil.in.ua\"/>\n*2019: $4.08 Billion (UAH 102 billion) <ref name=\"mil.in.ua\"/>\n*2020: $5.2 billion (UAH 130 billion) <ref>https://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2019/11/14/7231954/</ref>\n\n\"Security and Defense\" combined budget apart from Department of Defense (Defense Ministry) for Armed Forces of Ukraine, also includes expenses for Police, Customs, and Border Control.\n\n== Military holidays ==\n[[File:\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0456\u043d\u0441\u043f\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0443\u0432\u0430\u0432 \u0431\u043e\u0439\u043e\u0432\u0456 \u043d\u0430\u0432\u0447\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044f \u0417\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0439\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u0421\u0438\u043b \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 2.jpg|thumb|[[T-64]] and [[Su-27]] on [[Defender of Ukraine Day]] celebration, 14 October 2017]]\nThese are the military holidays observed by all service personnel the Ukrainian Armed Forces.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mil.gov.ua/index.php?lang=en&part=history&sub=holidays|title=\u041c\u0456\u043d\u0456\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e|access-date=2008-11-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071109150548/http://www.mil.gov.ua/index.php?lang=en&part=history&sub=holidays|archive-date=2007-11-09|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n* May 23 \u2013 Naval Infantry Day\n* July 8 \u2013 Air and Air Defence Forces Day\n* First Sunday in July \u2013 [[Navy Day (Ukraine)|Navy Day]];<ref name=pndfsj>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/271853.html Ukrainian Navy to celebrate its holiday on first Sunday of July \u2013 decree] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150716175200/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/271853.html |date=2015-07-16 }}, [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (12 June 2015)</ref> From 1997 till 2011 this day was celebrated on August 1<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3NJt5Un2AEAC&pg=PA781&dq=Ukrainian+%22Navy+day%22#v=onepage&q=Ukrainian%20%22Navy%20day%22&f=false|title=The Global Road Warrior: 100 Country Handbook for the International Business Traveler|first=Joe|last=Reif|authorlink=Joe Reif|page=781|edition=3|publisher=[[World Trade Press]]|year=2001|isbn=1-885073-86-0|access-date=2015-11-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160204213432/https://books.google.com/books?id=3NJt5Un2AEAC&pg=PA781&dq=Ukrainian+%22Navy+day%22&hl=nl&sa=X&ei=46oIT6PvJcKAOojRxZsB&ved=0CEMQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=Ukrainian%20%22Navy%20day%22&f=false|archive-date=2016-02-04|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AsQzDd41doAC&pg=PA250&lpg=PA250&dq=Ukrainian+Navy++August+1,+1992#v=onepage&q=Ukrainian%20Navy%20%20August%201%2C%201992&f=false|title=Ukraine Intelligence & Security Activities and Operations Handbook|page=250|publisher=[[International Business Publications, USA]]|year=2009|isbn=978-0-7397-1661-8|access-date=2015-11-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511133159/https://books.google.com/books?id=AsQzDd41doAC&pg=PA250&lpg=PA250&dq=Ukrainian+Navy++August+1,+1992&source=bl&ots=yJuER86KK2&sig=bCgBoY4nj2wTJXZMp0piUt8MwuQ&hl=nl&sa=X&ei=O68IT9fTGY3m-gaxoPXGCw&sqi=2&ved=0CEUQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=Ukrainian%20Navy%20%20August%201%2C%201992&f=false|archive-date=2016-05-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* August 8 \u2013 Signal Corps Day\n* September 7 \u2013 [[Chief directorate of intelligence of the Ministry of Defence of Ukraine|Military Intelligence]] Forces Day\n* September 9 \u2013 [[Armored Force (Ukraine)|Armoured Forces]] Day\n* September 14 \u2013 Mobilized Servicemen Day\n* October 14 \u2013 [[Defender of Ukraine Day]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://zakon3.rada.gov.ua/laws/show/806/2014|title=\u041f\u0440\u043e \u0414\u0435\u043d\u044c \u0437\u0430\u0445\u0438\u0441\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 {{!}} \u0432\u0456\u0434 14 October 2014 \u2116 806/2014|date=14 October 2014|website=zakon3.rada.gov.ua|language=uk|trans-title=On the day of defenders of Ukraine {{!}} 14 October 2014 No. 806/2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160302215112/http://zakon3.rada.gov.ua/laws/show/806/2014|archive-date=2 March 2016|access-date=2 March 2016}}</ref>\n* October 29 \u2013 Finance Officers Day\n* November 3 \u2013 [[Rocket Forces and Artillery (Ukraine)|Rocket Forces and Artillery]] Day\n* November 3 \u2013 Corps of Engineers Day\n* November 21 \u2013 [[Ukrainian Air Assault Forces|Air Assault Forces]] Day <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2017/11/8/7161138/|title=\u0414\u0435\u043d\u044c \u0434\u0435\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0456\u0432 \u0432\u0438\u0440\u0456\u0448\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438|website=\u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0434\u0430|accessdate=27 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180113232044/http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2017/11/8/7161138/|archive-date=13 January 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3802017-23058 |title=\u0423\u043a\u0430\u0437 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 \u2116380/2017 \u0432\u0456\u0434 21 \u043b\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043f\u0430\u0434\u0430 2017 \u0440\u043e\u043a\u0443 \"\u041f\u0440\u043e \u0414\u0435\u043d\u044c \u0414\u0435\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0442\u043d\u043e-\u0448\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0445 \u0432\u0456\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a \u0417\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0439\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u0421\u0438\u043b \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438\" |date=2017-11-21 |website=president.gov.ua |publisher=\u0410\u0434\u043c\u0456\u043d\u0456\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0456\u044f \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 |access-date=2017-12-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201032136/http://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3802017-23058 |archive-date=2017-12-01 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Poroshenko: 469 Ukrainian paratroopers killed in Donbas amid war|url=https://www.unian.info/war/2254451-poroshenko-469-ukrainian-paratroopers-killed-in-donbas-amid-war.html|work=UNIAN|access-date=2017-12-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201042554/https://www.unian.info/war/2254451-poroshenko-469-ukrainian-paratroopers-killed-in-donbas-amid-war.html|archive-date=2017-12-01|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* December 6 \u2013 [[Armed Forces Day]]; festive fireworks and salutes take place in various cities in Ukraine<ref>[http://www.unian.net/eng/news/news-350150.html Festive fireworks and salutes to take place in 9 cities on Sunday] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101224211520/http://www.unian.net/eng/news/news-350150.html |date=2010-12-24 }}, [[UNIAN]] (December 3, 2009)</ref> The holiday was established in 1993 by the [[Ukrainian parliament]].<ref>[https://www.unian.info/m/society/2282449-ukraine-marks-armed-forces-day-video.html Ukraine marks Armed Forces Day (Video)], [[UNIAN]] (06 December 2017)</ref>\n* December 12 \u2013 [[Ukrainian Ground Forces|Ground Forces]] Day\n* December 23 \u2013 Operational Servicemen Day\n\n== Veterans ==\nUkraine provides combat veterans with a range of benefits. Ukrainians who served in WWII, the [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War]], or as [[Liquidator (Chernobyl)|liquidators]] at the [[Chernobyl disaster]] are eligible for benefits such as monthly allowances, discounts on medical and pharmacy services, free use of public transportation, additional vacation days from work, retention priority in work layoffs, easier access to loans and associated approval processes, preference when applying for security related positions, priority when applying to vocational schools or trade schools, and electricity, gas, and housing subsidies. Veterans are also eligible to stay at military sanatoriums, space permitting. Since gaining independence, Ukraine has deployed troops to Kosovo, Iraq, and Afghanistan, gaining a new generation of veterans separate from those who have served in the Soviet forces. Most recently, the government passed a law extending veteran benefits to Ukrainian troops responding to the [[War in Donbass]]. Moreover, veterans from other nations who move to or reside in Ukraine may be eligible for some of the listed benefits, this provision was likely made to ensure WWII, Chernobyl, and Afghanistan veterans from other Soviet states who moved to Ukraine received similar benefits, however as Ukraine has participated in numerous NATO-led conflicts since its independence, it is unclear if NATO veterans would be extended these benefits.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timlawyer.com.ua/lgoti-voenoslugashim-uchastnikam-ato/|title=Benefits for the servicemen of the ATO|publisher=\u0425\u0430\u0440\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0422\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0445\u043e\u0432|date=2014-09-08|access-date=2014-10-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141009145108/http://timlawyer.com.ua/lgoti-voenoslugashim-uchastnikam-ato|archive-date=2014-10-09|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nVeteran groups are not as developed as in the United States which has numerous well known national organizations such as the [[Veterans of Foreign Wars]]. World War II veterans, and even persons who have lived through the war are generally treated with the highest respect. Other veterans are not as well known. Ukrainian veterans from the Soviet War of Afghanistan are strikingly similar to the Vietnam veterans of the United States. The Soviet Union generally kept the public in the dark through the war, unlike in Vietnam where coverage was very high, Afghanistan is often labeled as a mistake by the Soviet Union and its successor states, the lack of media coverage and censorship through the war also ensured that many still remain unaware of their nations involvement in the conflict.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vvaw.org/veteran/article/?id=61&print=yes|title=Afghanistan Veteran Once Removed|website=vvaw.org|publisher=Vietnam Veterans Against the War|access-date=2016-03-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304003643/http://www.vvaw.org/veteran/article/?id=61&print=yes|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite Ukraine having the 3rd largest contingent of troops in Iraq in 2004, few also realize that their nation has many veterans of the Iraq war.\n\nDue to the ongoing conflict with pro-Russian separatists, another generation of veterans appeared in Ukraine. These veterans would be eligible for the same benefits as all others. However, as there was no official declaration of war it was difficult to determine the cut-off date for veteran benefits, leaving many that participated at the beginning of the conflict without benefits. At first, Ukraine only gave benefits posthumously to family members as there was no legal framework to account for the veterans, moreover, members of territorial defense battalions were not eligible for benefits at all. In August, a law was passed granting all service members participating in Ukraine's Anti-Terror Operation the status of veterans, five months after first hostilities broke out in Crimea, the territorial defense battalions were integrated into the National Guard making them part of Ukraine's forces, thus allowing their volunteers to receive veteran status.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://censor.net.ua/news/305860/status_uchastnika_boevyh_deyistviyi_boyitsy_ato_poka_poluchayut_tolko_posmertno|publisher=censor|title=\u0421\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0443\u0441 \u0443\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0431\u043e\u0435\u0432\u044b\u0445 \u0434\u0435\u0439\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0438\u0439 \u0431\u043e\u0439\u0446\u044b \u0410\u0422\u041e \u043f\u043e\u043a\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0430\u044e\u0442 \u0442\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043a\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0441\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0442\u043d\u043e|access-date=2014-12-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141010004717/http://censor.net.ua/news/305860/status_uchastnika_boevyh_deyistviyi_boyitsy_ato_poka_poluchayut_tolko_posmertno|archive-date=2014-10-10|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gazeta.zn.ua/internal/uchastnik-boevyh-deystviy-nerealnaya-mechta-uchastnika-ato-_.html|publisher=Gazaeta|title=\u0423\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a \u0431\u043e\u0435\u0432\u044b\u0445 \u0434\u0435\u0439\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0438\u0439. \u041d\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043c\u0435\u0447\u0442\u0430 \u0443\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0410\u0422\u041e|access-date=2014-12-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150111113053/http://gazeta.zn.ua/internal/uchastnik-boevyh-deystviy-nerealnaya-mechta-uchastnika-ato-_.html|archive-date=2015-01-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nVeterans of the so-called \"ATO\"-operations in Donbas are eligible for receiving apartments (if staying in active duty) or a land plot for building purposes of 1000 sqm. in the district of their registration.\n\nOn 22 November 2018 the [[Ministry for Veterans Affairs]] of Ukraine was officially established.<ref name=\"UGF10145168MVA\">[https://www.unian.info/m/politics/10348734-ukraine-parliament-appoints-markarova-friz-ministers.html Ukraine parliament appoints Markarova, Friz ministers], [[UNIAN]] (22 November 2018)</ref>\n\n== Military industrial complex ==\n{{Main|Ukroboronprom}}\n\nUkraine received about 30% of the [[Soviet military]] industry, which included between 50 and 60 percent of all Ukrainian [[Company|enterprises]], employing 40% of its working population. Ukraine was, and still remains, a leader in [[missile]]-related technology,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fas.org/nuke/guide/ukraine/index.html|title=Ukraine Special Weapons|access-date=2015-11-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151126064545/https://fas.org/nuke/guide/ukraine/index.html|archive-date=2015-11-26|url-status=live}}</ref> [[navigation]] electronics for combat vessels and [[submarine]]s, [[guidance system]]s, and [[radar]] for military [[Jet aircraft|jets]], heavy armoured vehicles.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* James Sherr, 'Ukraine's Defence Reform: An Update', [[Conflict Studies Research Centre]], 2002\n* Melanie Bright, The Jane's Interview: Yevhen Marchuk, Ukraine's Minister of Defence, Jane's Defence Weekly, 7 January 2004\n* John Jaworsky, \"Ukraine's Armed Forces and Military Policy,\" Harvard Ukrainian Studies Vol. 20, UKRAINE IN THE WORLD: Studies in the International Relations and Security Structure of a Newly Independent State (1996), pp.&nbsp;223\u2013247\n* Kuzio, T., \"Ukrainian Armed Forces in Crisis,\" ''[[Jane's Intelligence Review]]'', 1995, Vol. 7; No. 7, page 305\n* Kuzio, T., \"The organization of Ukraine's forces,\" ''[[Jane's Intelligence Review]]'', June 1996, Vol. 8; No. 6, pages 254-258\n* Ben Lombardia, \"Ukrainian armed forces: Defence expenditure and military reform,\" ''[[The Journal of Slavic Military Studies]]'', Volume 14, Issue 3, 2001, pages 31\u201368\n* {{cite journal |last1=Mychajlyszyn |first1=Natalie |year=2002 |title=Civil-Military Relations in Post-Soviet Ukraine: Implciations for Domestic and Regional Stability|journal=Armed Forces & Society |volume=28 |issue=3 |pages=455\u2013479 |publisher=Interuniversity Seminar on Armed Forces and Society |doi=10.1177/0095327x0202800306